<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="video-gen-tools">
  <metadata>
    <tier>geek</tier>
    <group>ai</group>
    <domain>multimodal-ai</domain>
    <summary>API client implementations for Runway Gen-3, Luma Dream Machine, and Replicate video models with production async VideoGenerationService including multi-provider fallback and retry logic.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>video-generation</tag>
      <tag>runway</tag>
      <tag>luma</tag>
      <tag>replicate</tag>
      <tag>async</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-26</created>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>Video Generation Tools</title>
    <summary>API client implementations for Runway Gen-3, Luma Dream Machine, and Replicate video models (SVD, AnimateDiff, Zeroscope). Includes a production async VideoGenerationService with multi-provider fallback, retry logic, and a stub for image upload that must be implemented per storage backend.</summary>
    <why>
      <p>Each provider has incompatible API shapes, async polling semantics, and URL expiry windows (30–60 min). A unified service layer with provider-specific adapters and immediate post-generation download prevents the most common production failures (expired URLs, missing timeouts, OOM from full-file-in-memory downloads).</p>
    </why>
    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Integrating Runway, Luma, or Replicate into an automated content pipeline</item>
        <item>Building multi-provider fallback logic for resilience</item>
        <item>Extending an existing video by appending new AI-generated segments</item>
        <item>Wrapping async generation in retry/timeout logic for production reliability</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>
    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Single one-off clip — use the web UI directly; API setup overhead is not justified</item>
        <item>Synchronous request/response architectures — all video APIs are async polling; this pattern will block</item>
        <item>When video quality is untested — validate provider outputs manually before automating at scale</item>
        <item>Latency-sensitive user flows (sub-2s response expected)</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>
    <section name="runway-gen-3">
      <p>Runway provides an official Python SDK. Tasks are async — poll with _wait_for_completion. Video URLs are pre-signed and expire in 30-60 minutes; download immediately after SUCCEEDED.</p>
      <example type="good" title="RunwayVideoGenerator implementation">
        <code lang="python"><![CDATA[
class RunwayVideoGenerator:
    def __init__(self):
        self.client = runwayml.RunwayML()

    def generate_from_text(self, prompt: str, duration: int = 5,
                           aspect_ratio: str = "16:9") -> dict:
        task = self.client.image_to_video.create(
            model="gen3a_turbo", prompt_text=prompt,
            duration=duration, ratio=aspect_ratio)
        return self._wait_for_completion(task.id)

    def _wait_for_completion(self, task_id: str, timeout: int = 300) -> dict:
        start_time = time.time()
        while time.time() - start_time < timeout:
            task = self.client.tasks.retrieve(task_id)
            if task.status == "SUCCEEDED":
                return {"status": "success", "video_url": task.output[0], "task_id": task_id}
            elif task.status == "FAILED":
                return {"status": "failed", "error": task.failure, "task_id": task_id}
            time.sleep(5)
        return {"status": "timeout", "task_id": task_id}
        ]]></code>
        <note>Runway content policy violations return FAILED with no useful error message. Do not retry without modifying the prompt.</note>
      </example>
    </section>
    <section name="luma-dream-machine">
      <p>Luma has no official Python SDK — use httpx REST calls. The original _wait_for_completion has no timeout; a fixed version is required for production.</p>
      <example type="good" title="LumaVideoGenerator with timeout fix">
        <code lang="python"><![CDATA[
def _wait_for_completion(self, generation_id: str, timeout: int = 300) -> dict:
    """Fixed version with timeout — original loops infinitely."""
    start = time.time()
    while time.time() - start < timeout:
        response = requests.get(
            f"{self.base_url}/generations/{generation_id}",
            headers={"Authorization": f"Bearer {self.api_key}"}
        )
        gen = response.json()
        if gen["state"] == "completed":
            return {"status": "success",
                    "video_url": gen["assets"]["video"], "id": generation_id}
        elif gen["state"] == "failed":
            return {"status": "failed",
                    "error": gen.get("failure_reason"), "id": generation_id}
        time.sleep(5)
    return {"status": "timeout", "id": generation_id}
        ]]></code>
        <note>Luma video extension uses generation IDs (not video URLs) in keyframes.frame0. Agents must track IDs, not just URLs.</note>
      </example>
    </section>
    <section name="replicate-models">
      <p>Replicate returns an iterator or URL depending on model and output type. output[0] fails if output is not a list. Pin model version hashes in config — they go stale as providers update.</p>
      <example type="good" title="Stable Video Diffusion via Replicate">
        <code lang="python"><![CDATA[
def generate_stable_video(self, image_path: str, motion_bucket_id: int = 127) -> str:
    output = replicate.run(
        # Pin hash — update intentionally, not automatically
        "stability-ai/stable-video-diffusion:3f0457e4619daac51203dedb472816fd4af51f3149fa7a9e0b5ffcf1b8172438",
        input={"input_image": open(image_path, "rb"),
               "motion_bucket_id": motion_bucket_id, "fps": 7, "num_frames": 25}
    )
    return output  # returns URL string for SVD
        ]]></code>
      </example>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Assuming output[0] works for all Replicate models.</description>
        <reason>Replicate returns an iterator or a URL string depending on the model. Calling [0] on a string iterator returns the first character.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
    <section name="video-generation-service">
      <p>VideoGenerationService abstracts provider selection, retry logic, and post-generation download into a single async generate() call. The _upload_image method is a stub — must be implemented per storage backend before image-to-video works.</p>
      <example type="good" title="VideoGenerationService with multi-provider routing">
        <code lang="python"><![CDATA[
@dataclass
class VideoGenerationConfig:
    provider: VideoProvider = VideoProvider.REPLICATE
    default_duration: int = 5
    default_aspect_ratio: str = "16:9"
    max_retries: int = 3
    timeout: int = 600
    output_dir: str = "./generated_videos"

class VideoGenerationService:
    async def generate(self, prompt: str,
                       provider: Optional[VideoProvider] = None, **kwargs) -> dict:
        provider = provider or self.config.provider
        for attempt in range(self.config.max_retries):
            try:
                result = await self._dispatch(provider, prompt, **kwargs)
                if result["status"] == "success":
                    output_path = await self._download_video(result["video_url"], prompt[:50])
                    result["local_path"] = output_path
                return result
            except Exception as e:
                if attempt == self.config.max_retries - 1:
                    return {"status": "failed", "error": str(e)}
        ]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>
    <section name="production-rules">
      <rule>
        <statement>Download videos immediately after SUCCEEDED status. Pre-signed URLs from Runway and Luma expire in 30-60 minutes.</statement>
        <rationale>An archival agent that sweeps output_dir hours later will receive 404 on all cached provider URLs. Download on success, then serve from local storage.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Use streaming HTTP download for video files to avoid loading entire files into memory.</statement>
        <rationale>httpx async download that reads response.content buffers the full video before writing. A 100MB file breaks on memory-constrained hosts.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Log submitted prompt and task ID together at generation time. Store provider, model version, and seed for reproducibility.</statement>
        <rationale>Re-querying a failed task requires the task ID. Debugging quality issues requires knowing exactly which model version and seed produced the output.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Validate output file exists and size is greater than 0 before returning success from the service.</statement>
        <rationale>APIs can return SUCCEEDED status with empty output. Propagating an empty file path causes silent failures in downstream processing.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Passing a Runway task ID to a Luma polling endpoint or vice versa.</description>
        <reason>Task IDs and generation IDs are provider-specific and non-portable. Keep provider context alongside each ID.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
    <section name="agentic-workflow">
      <p>An agent receives a generation request with provider preference and prompt. It instantiates VideoGenerationService, calls generate(), awaits the async result, verifies the local path exists, then returns structured output with {status, local_path, video_url}. For multi-provider fallback, agents iterate providers list in order and stop on first success. A separate archival agent periodically sweeps output_dir and uploads to permanent storage (S3), since pre-signed video URLs expire.</p>
      <example type="good" title="Multi-provider selection pattern">
        <code lang="python"><![CDATA[
PROVIDER_MAP = {
    "photorealistic": VideoProvider.LUMA,
    "cinematic": VideoProvider.RUNWAY,
    "animated": VideoProvider.REPLICATE,
}
provider = PROVIDER_MAP.get(style_tag, VideoProvider.REPLICATE)
        ]]></code>
      </example>
      <example type="good" title="Agent prompt pattern">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[
<task>
Generate a video clip.
Provider: {{PROVIDER}}
Prompt: {{PROMPT}}
Duration: {{DURATION}}s
Aspect ratio: {{ASPECT_RATIO}}
Output dir: {{OUTPUT_DIR}}

Return JSON:
{"status": "success"|"failed", "local_path": "...", "error": "..."}
</task>
        ]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>
    <templates>
      <template path="templates/runway-generator.py" purpose="RunwayVideoGenerator: text-to-video and image-to-video via SDK"/>
      <template path="templates/luma-generator.py" purpose="LumaVideoGenerator: generate, extend, image-to-video via REST"/>
      <template path="templates/replicate-generator.py" purpose="ReplicateVideoGenerator: SVD, AnimateDiff, Zeroscope"/>
      <template path="templates/video-service.py" purpose="VideoGenerationService with async multi-provider routing"/>
      <template path="templates/prompt-generate.txt" purpose="Agent prompt pattern for dispatching and polling a generation job"/>
    </templates>
    <section name="tools-and-cli">
      <p>The following CLI tools and SDKs are essential for video generation workflows:</p>
      <list>
        <item>runwayml (Python SDK) — Runway Gen-3 API client. Install: pip install runwayml. Docs: docs.runwayml.com</item>
        <item>replicate (Python SDK) — Replicate model runner. Install: pip install replicate. Docs: replicate.com/docs</item>
        <item>httpx — Async HTTP for Luma API and video download. Install: pip install httpx</item>
        <item>ffmpeg — Post-processing: concat, trim, resize. Install: apt install ffmpeg</item>
        <item>boto3 — S3 upload for permanent video storage. Install: pip install boto3</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="services-and-providers">
      <p>Production-grade video generation services: Runway Gen-3 (SaaS, official Python SDK, best structured API), Luma Dream Machine (SaaS, REST API, keyframe control for extend/chaining), Replicate (SaaS model marketplace, pin versions via hash, lowest cost), Zeroscope v2 XL (OSS on Replicate, good baseline, 576x320 max), AnimateDiff (OSS on Replicate, better for animated/stylized content), Stable Video Diffusion (OSS on Replicate, img2video with motion_bucket_id control), Cloudinary (SaaS video storage/transform/CDN for serving generated clips).</p>
    </section>
    <section name="best-practices">
      <rule>
        <statement>Always download videos immediately after SUCCEEDED — pre-signed URLs expire in 30–60 minutes depending on provider.</statement>
        <rationale>Provider URLs are time-bound. Caching without download will fail hours later.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Pin Replicate model hashes to a known-good version; record them in a config file, not inline in code.</statement>
        <rationale>Model versions go stale and produce different outputs. Explicit pinning ensures reproducibility.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Implement provider-level rate limiting (Runway: 10 concurrent tasks; Luma: varies by plan).</statement>
        <rationale>Each provider enforces quotas. Exceeding them returns errors that block the pipeline.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Use streaming download for large files (httpx stream mode or requests with stream=True) to avoid OOM.</statement>
        <rationale>Full-file-in-memory buffering breaks on constrained hosts and large video files.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Log both the submitted prompt and the task ID together; re-querying failed tasks requires the task ID.</statement>
        <rationale>Without structured logging, failed jobs cannot be re-queried or debugged.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Store provider, model version, prompt, seed, and output path in a generation log for reproducibility.</statement>
        <rationale>Debugging quality issues requires knowing exactly which model version and seed produced the output.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Use separate output directories per provider to simplify debugging and cost attribution.</statement>
        <rationale>Mixed output directories make it hard to trace which provider produced which clip.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="agent-gotchas">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Runway SDK image_to_video.create requires an image URL even for text-only generation on some model versions.</description>
        <reason>Have a fallback blank image URL ready; verify endpoint with current SDK docs before use.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Replicate returns an iterator or a URL depending on model and output type; output[0] fails if output is not a list.</description>
        <reason>Each model has different output shapes. Check type before indexing.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Luma keyframes.frame0.type = "generation" for extension requires the source generation ID, not the video URL.</description>
        <reason>Agents must track IDs, not just URLs, for chaining operations across the same provider.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>VideoGenerationService.extend_video extracts frames from a local file then re-uploads; if the source clip was generated by a different provider, seams are visible.</description>
        <reason>Cross-provider stitching produces discontinuities in motion and color.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Async _upload_image is a stub in VideoGenerationService.</description>
        <reason>Any agent that calls generate_from_image(image_path=...) will hit NotImplementedError until implemented per storage backend.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Task IDs and generation IDs are provider-specific and non-portable; never pass a Runway task ID to a Luma polling call.</description>
        <reason>Provider contexts are incompatible. Keep provider alongside ID.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Error messages from Runway on content policy violations are terse ("FAILED") with no explanation.</description>
        <reason>Agent must not retry without modifying the prompt when FAILED is returned.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
    <section name="subagent-roles">
      <p>Recommended subagent specialization: Haiku executes generation calls, polls, downloads, and returns structured result. Sonnet selects provider based on prompt type (photorealistic → Luma; anime → Replicate/AnimateDiff; commercial → Runway). Haiku performs video URL archival: sweeps output dir, uploads to S3, updates metadata store.</p>
    </section>
    <see-also>
      <link href="https://docs.runwayml.com"/>
